vectorData.altText: That's right! Notice Mickey Mouse’s ears, the cerebral peduncles, reaching ventrally and a pair of colliculi dorsally. Notice also the interpeduncular fossa and cerebral aqueduct.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

In Functional Neuroanatomy, in the Spinal Cord and Brainstem series, compare sections 15 (rostral midbrain) and 14 (caudal midbrain) to the axon-stained sections of the rostral and caudal midbrain that I provided. In these images, identify the cerebral peduncles (basis pedunculi), interpeduncular fossa, colliculi and cerebral aqueduct. 
Notice that at this level, the cerebral peduncles “reach” anteriorly toward the cerebral hemispheres.
Now look at Transverse Series of MRIs, sections 8 (rostral midbrain) and 7 (caudal midbrain). Again, in these images, identify the cerebral peduncles, interpeduncular fossa and colliculi. 
This characteristic shape, with the cerebral peduncles “reaching” anteriorly with the interpeduncular fossa in between, and the colliculi located posteriorly identifies the midbrain in MRI.  
Some people say a cross section of the midbrain reminds them of Mickey Mouse.
Now, use the “Self Test” function, and see how you do!

Be sure you can identify features A through D. See answers here     .
With reference to the illustrations of the brainstem provided, the brainstem model, and your brainstem specimens, identify surface features and spaces A through E.
